-- grouped queues --

the killer feature is grouped concurrency. queue.group(key) gives each key
its own isolated queue with its own concurrency/delay settings. perfect for
per-tenant rate limiting.

```js
await queue.group('tenant-123').push({ action: 'sync' })
```

with concurrency: 1 per group, only one task per tenant runs at a time.
different tenants process in parallel.

-- horizontal scaling --

multiple server instances can push to the same queue. redis coordinates via
atomic brPop. tasks are processed exactly once (no duplicates).

events are LOCAL only - only the processing server emits complete/failed.
for distributed events, use redis pub/sub or mesh-kit broadcasting.

-- integration with mesh-kit --

queue uses `queue:*` redis keys, mesh uses `mesh:*`. they share the same
redis instance and DB without conflicts.

common pattern: include a connectionId in the task payload, then use
mesh.sendTo() on completion to deliver results to the specific client:

```js
await queue.group(tenantId).push({ connectionId, action: 'generate' })

queue.on('complete', ({ task, result }) => {
  mesh.sendTo(task.payload.connectionId, 'job:complete', result)
})

queue.on('failed', ({ task, error }) => {
  mesh.sendTo(task.payload.connectionId, 'job:failed', { error: error.message })
})
```

if you want to notify everyone in a room instead of a single connection:

```js
await queue.push({ roomKey: 'project:abc', action: 'rebuild' })

queue.on('complete', ({ task, result }) => {
  mesh.broadcastRoom(task.payload.roomKey, 'build:complete', result)
})
```

queue events are local-only - if you have multiple server instances, only
the instance that processed the task can call sendTo/broadcastRoom. this
works because mesh.sendTo and mesh.broadcastRoom route cross-instance via
redis pub/sub internally.

-- cleanup --

always call queue.close() on shutdown. it stops workers, clears timers,
disconnects from redis.

-- delay format --

delay and timeout accept strings: '100ms', '5s', '1m', etc. or plain
numbers as milliseconds.
